       cout << "TEST " << x.at(n) << endl;
     } catch (std::out_of_range&) {
       cout << "Index out of bounds: " << n << endl;
     }
   }
   ```
   
   - An even more robust design involves refining your code logic to naturally
   avoid out-of-bounds accesses, potentially redesigning how indices are
   calculated based on application requirements rather than excessive
